                  <h3>Rotna</h3>
                  <p>Rotna is a traditional dish from the Garhwal and Kumaon regions of Uttarakhand, often prepared during festivals, special occasions, or as a comforting meal. It is a type of flatbread made from rice flour and is commonly served with a variety of vegetable dishes or chutneys.</p>
                  <h3>Key Features:</h3>
                  <h4>1. Ingredients:</h4>
                  <p>Rice flour (main ingredient)
   Water
   Salt (optional, for flavor)
   Sometimes, a little ghee or oil for extra softness
</p>
                  <h4>2. Preparation:</h4>
                  <p>- The rice flour is mixed with warm water and kneaded into a smooth dough.
   - The dough is divided into small balls and rolled out into flat discs or round shapes, similar to other types of Indian flatbreads like chapati or roti.
   - These discs are then roasted on a hot griddle (tava) until they turn golden brown and crispy. Some variations include cooking them in ghee or oil to enhance flavor.
   - Once cooked, the rotna is served hot.
</p>
                  <h4>3. Taste:</h4>
                  <p>Rotna has a soft and slightly chewy texture when freshly made. It’s more neutral in flavor compared to wheat-based breads, making it perfect for pairing with spicy or tangy vegetable curries.</p>
                  <h4>4. Serving:</h4>
                  <p>Typically served with dal (lentils), vegetable curries, or chutneys.
   Can also be enjoyed with yogurt or pickles, making it a versatile and satisfying dish.
</p>
                  <h4>5. Significance:</h4> 
                  <p>Rotna is a staple in Uttarakhand's traditional diet, especially in rural areas where rice is a common crop.
  It’s especially popular during festivals or in colder months because it provides warmth and sustenance.
This simple and nutritious dish showcases the use of locally available ingredients like rice flour, making it an important part of the cultural and culinary traditions of Uttarakhand.
</p> 
